      "content": "Explain how to find the mass percentage of a solute."
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "To find the mass percentage of a solute, you use the formula: mass of the solute times 100 divided by the total mass of the solution (solute plus solvent). For example, if you dissolve 25 grams of sugar in 100 grams of water, the mass percentage would be (25 x 100) / (25 + 100), which equals 20%. It's similar to figuring out how much of your meal is made up of rice versus vegetables. What kind of solution are you thinking about calculating the percentage for?"
